Part I - Ford GoBike System Data

by: Ibtisam Alzahrani

Introduction

The chosen dataset is Ford GoBike System Data. The dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

So far i got a couple of to-dos here:

  • Convert start_time/end_time to datetime type.
  • Convert Member_virth_year to integer type.
  • Convert duration from seconds to minutes.
  • Drop missing values.
  • Perhaps we'll need a day-of-week column to get better insights on trips.

Let's start cleaning up!

In[6]:
# make a copy
df_cleaned = df.copy()
In[7]:
# drop null values
df_cleaned.dropna(inplace=True)
In[8]:
# convert start_time/end_time to datetime 
df_cleaned['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_cleaned['start_time'])
df_cleaned['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_cleaned['end_time'])
In[9]:
# convert member birth year to int
df_cleaned['member_birth_year'] = df_cleaned['member_birth_year'].astype('int64')
In[10]:
# add new column for start_date weekday
df_cleaned['weekday'] = df_cleaned['start_time'].dt.day_name()
In[11]:
# convert duration from seconds to minutes
df_cleaned['duration_sec'] = df_cleaned['duration_sec'] / 60
df_cleaned.rename(columns = {'duration_sec' : 'duration_min'}, inplace=True)
In[12]:
# convert duration_min to int
df_cleaned['duration_min'] = df_cleaned['duration_min'].astype('int64')
In[13]:
# get member birth years from 1950 and up
df_cleaned = df_cleaned[df_cleaned['member_birth_year'] > 1950]

What is the structure of your dataset?

This dataset consists of 183,412 rows and 16 columns. We have 16 features ready to be explored and broken down to better understand our data.

These are the oclumns:

  • duration_min - int64
  • start_time - datetime
  • end_time - datetime
  • start_station_id - float64
  • start_station_name - object
  • start_station_latitude - float64
  • start_station_longitude - float64
  • end_station_id - float64
  • end_station_name - object
  • end_station_latitude - float64
  • end_station_longitude - float64
  • bike_id - int64
  • user_type - object
  • member_birth_year - int64
  • member_gender - object
  • bike_share_for_all_trip - object
  • weekday - object

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I'm interested in answering/knowing:

  • Who uses the bike-sharing (Gender/Age)?
  • What's the average trip duration overall?
  • What days have more bike-riding trips than others?
  • How user type affects bike trips (Customers/subscribers)?
  • Most frequent bike stations the riders go to?
  • Most frequent start hour?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Features such as duration_min, user_type, gender, member_birth_year, weekday, start_time ..etc.

# reusable plotting functions
def countplot(rotate_x_label = False, variable_one = '', x_label = '', y_label = '', title = '', order=None):
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
    if (rotate_x_label == True):
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        ax=sns.countplot(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, order=order)
        ax.set(xlabel=x_label,
                ylabel=y_label,
                title=title)
        plt.show();
        
    else:
        ax=sns.countplot(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, order=order)
        ax.set(xlabel=x_label,
                ylabel=y_label,
                title=title)
        plt.show();
            
    
def histplot(rotate_x_label = False, variable_one = '', x_label = '', y_label = '', title = '', bins = 5):
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
    if (rotate_x_label == True):
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        plt.hist(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, bins=bins)
        plt.xlabel=x_label,
        plt.ylabel=y_label,
        plt.title=title
        plt.show();
        
    else:
        plt.hist(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, bins=bins)
        plt.xlabel=x_label,
        plt.ylabel=y_label,
        plt.title=title
        plt.show();

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?

  • We've seen how male riders are way larger in numbers than female riders (Males: 120k+, Females: Approximately: 40k).
  • Trip duration usually takes from 5-15 mins.
  • Most Riders are "Subscribers" and only few customers.
  • Riders have more trips on Thursday, and less trips on weekends (Saturday, Sunday).
  • Most riders are of age 29-35.
  • Most frequent trip start station is "Powell St BART Station", follows it "Page St at Scott St" and others shown in the graph.
  • Most frequent trip start hours are 8AM and 5PM.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

No unusual distribution so far. I had to perform some data cleaning such as removing missing values, converting column types and creating new features/columns.

I investigated the relationship between Trip duration with age & gender. We saw age having no major effect trip duration. However there was a clear correlation between age and trip duration, as older riders tend to have short trips, and younger riders have longer trips.

# reusable plotting functions
def pointplot(rotate_x_label = False, variable_one = '',variable_two = '',variable_three = '', x_label = '', y_label = '', title = '', order=None):
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
    if (rotate_x_label == True):
        plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        ax=sns.pointplot(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, y = variable_two, hue=variable_three, errorbar=None, order=order )
        ax.set(xlabel=x_label,
                ylabel=y_label,
                title=title)
        plt.show();
        
    else:
        ax=sns.pointplot(data = df_cleaned, x = variable_one, order=order)
        ax.set(xlabel=x_label,
                ylabel=y_label,
                title=title)
        plt.show();

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

These charts conveyed the relationships we analyzed earlier. We've seen how weekday impacts trip duration (longer trips on weekends). We've also seen how gender and age impact trip duration, especially gender group "Other".

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

I was surprised to see gender of type "Other" and of age between 24-27 having longer trips. I also didn't expect that trip start hours from 1AM to 4AM being the longer trips, with mostly "Other" and "Female" riders.

Conclusions

  • Majority of riders are Males.
  • Average trip duration is between 5-15 mins.
  • Users of age 29-35 have more trips.
  • Subscribers users are the majority.
  • Trip duration (start time) is longer from 1AM - 4AM.
  • "Other" gender and younger riders have longer trips than others.
  • Start hours 8AM and 5PM have more trips than the rest.
  • Weekend having less but longer trips.
